<div id="review_2745787471" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2745787471" />
    <a title="Ryan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1500718-ryan"><img alt="Ryan" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1238846167p2/1500718.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2745787471?book_show_action=true">Mar 10, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ryan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ryan" href="/user/show/1500718-ryan">Ryan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780007209040" href="/book/show/227477.Six_Degrees">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1500718-ryan?shelf=eco">eco</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2745787471" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16942087081624493969"><i>Six Degrees</i> (2008) provides an overview of climate science, organized around what&apos;s expected to happen to Earth (Eaarth?) after each degree celsius increase in the planet&apos;s average temperature. What are climate models -- and where does the data that supports them come from? If these are questions you&apos;ve asked, then Lynas provides a pretty readable answer that I&apos;m not sure can be topped beyond getting into academic discourse.<br/><br/>I don&apos;t think I understood until reading this book why policy so often a</span>
  <span id="freeText16942087081624493969" style="display:none"><i>Six Degrees</i> (2008) provides an overview of climate science, organized around what's expected to happen to Earth (Eaarth?) after each degree celsius increase in the planet's average temperature. What are climate models -- and where does the data that supports them come from? If these are questions you've asked, then Lynas provides a pretty readable answer that I'm not sure can be topped beyond getting into academic discourse.<br /><br />I don't think I understood until reading this book why policy so often aspires to limit warming to two degrees celsius. Warming up to two degrees sucks. Greenhouse gases cause radiation to stay in our atmosphere longer than it would otherwise, so there's more heat in the atmosphere and in the ocean. That energy produces powerful hurricanes, it melts glaciers, and it causes the ocean to become more acidic. We should expect longer forest fire seasons. Fresh water supplies from mountain snowpacks are reduced or eventually eliminated, coastlines are covered or threatened by floods, and biodiversity is already reduced within the two degree window. We also get more heat waves, which I suppose we understand as days the weather person warns us about "extreme-heat warnings." I don't think I ever understood why heat waves are so bad for people until now, but if people are overheated and cannot cool down overnight, it's very hard on their body, which is why people die during heat waves. This is the optimistic two degree window we're shooting for.<br /><br />But it's also a bit of a gamble. If heat waves stress plants enough, it turns out they release stored carbon rather than absorbing more of it--a positive feedback loop. These feedback loops are tricky to account for, but they're one reason to pay attention to Arctic ice cover. As we lose things that reflect sunlight (ice) we absorb more heat from the sun in the dark green-blue ocean, another positive feedback loop. And there is also a lot of carbon stored in the tundra, so as the permafrost melts, that methane is released, another positive feedback loop. Unfortunately, the ice is melting a bit faster than was originally predicted because glaciers don't melt like an ice cube in a glass of scotch. Carbon stored in trees is also released by forest fires. It's not hard to find stories about these processes in the news.<br /><br />I suspect the value of Lynas's book is that it takes all those individual news stories we read about and explains how they connect--and why they're worth paying attention to. So much of science reporting is awful, but I wonder if climate science reporting is constrained as much by audience ignorance as other factors. I consequently found the most useful chapters were the first three and the final one. Expectations for 5 and 6 degrees read... not like science fiction so much as a version of the planet that is nearly incomprehensible. I also learned a lot. I don't think I ever fully appreciated, for example, how big a role the ocean plays in the planet's heat until now. Our CO2 levels are off the charts, geologically speaking, but because atmospheric concentration has risen so quickly, we don't yet see the temperatures of, say, the Cretaceous Period because the oceans are still absorbing heat.<br /><br />Climate science is pretty amazing, particularly the way it advances and in the way that it is in a constant race against human choices. When Lynas wrote <i>Six Degrees</i> in 2008, people were still hoping to curb CO2 concentrations at 400 PPM, but last I checked, we'd reached about 410, not including measures for CO2e. I'd be happy to read an updated version of this book now that we're ten years further into shameful process. I wonder if the "sequel" is David Wallace-Well's <i>Uninhabitable Earth</i>.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16942087081624493969" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

