    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_695430652" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/695430652" />
    <a title="John Gordon" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5863754-john-gordon"><img alt="John Gordon" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1321005153p2/5863754.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/695430652?book_show_action=true">Aug 15, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="John Gordon" class="user" itemprop="url" name="John Gordon" href="/user/show/5863754-john-gordon">John Gordon</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780007209040" href="/book/show/227477.Six_Degrees">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5863754-john-gordon?shelf=science">science</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer695430652" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5458194684304881129">Six degrees: Our future on a Hotter Planet is a challenging and confronting read. The author [Mark Lynas] has researched current scientific peer reviewed literature and presented it in a popular science format looking at the future of our planet at various temperature levels above pre-industrial. The style is quite readable, tending to move from one case study to another, the reason I say it is challenging is because of what it contains. Climate scientists have been telling governments about cli</span>
  <span id="freeText5458194684304881129" style="display:none">Six degrees: Our future on a Hotter Planet is a challenging and confronting read. The author [Mark Lynas] has researched current scientific peer reviewed literature and presented it in a popular science format looking at the future of our planet at various temperature levels above pre-industrial. The style is quite readable, tending to move from one case study to another, the reason I say it is challenging is because of what it contains. Climate scientists have been telling governments about climate change and the problems with CO2 emissions since the 70’s and yet our governments continue to fail to address the problem seriously. So, that leaves us with the question of where we are headed.<br /><br />The book allocates one chapter to each degree above pre-industrial and looks at the expected state of our planet at that level. Given that we are almost at 1° in the first chapter we read about the growth of deserts, water shortages, greater and more violent storms, heat waves, wild fires, the disappearance of the arctic sea ice, coral bleaching and the demise of the coral atolls under the rising seas. This is all happening already, is well researched and evidenced and is certainly bad enough.<br /><br />Then on to chapter two at 2°, the universally agreed target for emissions reductions. Even if we do manage (by some miracle) to reduce emissions to achieve 2° this is by no means a peachy future to which we have committed ourselves. Among other issues are ocean acidification, extreme heat waves, disappearance of glaciers – and consequent water supplies, massive biodiversity loss, bye bye ice cap and the polar bears. If this is not depressing enough then it only gets worse since the present lack of political will means that we are heading even beyond this. <br /><br />Chapter by chapter as things become progressively worse, suffice to say we do not want to go there. The later chapters are based more on paleo-climate research and what has happened in temperature / CO2 spikes in the past and adapted to our situation today. Of significant concern are the positive feedbacks pushing us past tipping points and the consequent spiralling out of control into a dramatically hotter world. For instance at 3° we can expect Amazonian collapse and soil carbon release of another 250 ppm of CO2 pushing us straight to 4°. Then the carbon and methane release from the Siberian permafrost may bump us up another degree. At 5° oceanic methane hydrate release could well push us to a mass extinction apocalypse of 6°. Bad tidings indeed.<br /><br />Without offering platitudes in the final chapter “Choosing our future” regarding renewable energy comfortably saving us the author ends with a summary of what is actually necessary to make a difference. This is a more important issue than the budget, immigration, education, football, the royals, dancing with the stars. Climate change is (or should be) the issue of the day. If we cannot get off our collective butts and address this issue worldwide, and soon, then we are f**ked. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="5458194684304881129" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


