    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1860077402" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1860077402" />
    <a title="Mark Denega" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/63315203-mark-denega"><img alt="Mark Denega" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1483308071p2/63315203.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1860077402?book_show_action=true">Jan 12, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mark Denega" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mark Denega" href="/user/show/63315203-mark-denega">Mark Denega</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780007209040" href="/book/show/227477.Six_Degrees">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1860077402" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3559886179007402359">Not the *best* book I&apos;ve read, but the most *important*, bar none. The text is dense, both because Lynas packs so much research into each chapter and because his writing style is somewhat superfluous, but read this book, nonetheless.<br/><br/>Six Degrees is an amalgamation of modern climate research--culled from scientific journals such as &apos;Science&apos; and &apos;Nature&apos;--and our understanding of past global heat events based on the fossil record, brought to life with descriptive detail by Lynas to illustrate what</span>
  <span id="freeText3559886179007402359" style="display:none">Not the *best* book I've read, but the most *important*, bar none. The text is dense, both because Lynas packs so much research into each chapter and because his writing style is somewhat superfluous, but read this book, nonetheless.<br /><br />Six Degrees is an amalgamation of modern climate research--culled from scientific journals such as 'Science' and 'Nature'--and our understanding of past global heat events based on the fossil record, brought to life with descriptive detail by Lynas to illustrate what the planet will look like with each successive degree of warming, and how humans will respond (e.g. water and food shortages in the expanding, uninhabitable deserts around the Earth's equator will lead to famine, and migration toward the more temperate north).<br /><br />After painting an apocalyptic picture in chapters 1-6, the author closes with a prevention plan to avoid 2-plus degrees of warming, the point at which many scientists believe positive feedback loops in greenhouse gas emissions will lead to unstoppable, runaway warming. In addition to an all-of-the-above action plan, which includes policy, *much* faster expansion of renewables, and large scale individual lifestyle changes to fossil fuel consumption, Lynas explains the evolutionary psychology of denial and breaks down the many excuses and logical fallacies (e.g. Tragedy of the Commons) that each of us makes to either blissfully ignore, or to not act on, climate change.<br /><br />Perhaps the most eye-opening takeaway from my follow-up research is that it's people who care about climate change most--"world-traveled greenies" --who are the biggest culprits of CO2 emissions. It's flying that usually contributes most to an individual's carbon footprint, and in the states, those who advocate for action against climate change tend to be educated, left-of-center travel junkies with a bit more money, flying frequently either to see the world or to visit family and friends in coastal US cities, to the detriment of the atmosphere.<br /><br />I'm guilty of this. Despite taking public transit to work, walking most other places, bringing reusable bags to the grocery store, eating little-to-no beef, unplugging household electronics overnight and while at work, and other low-carbon efforts, I still have an above average carbon footprint because of how much I fly each year. Lynas asks, as many have: are we willing to make sacrifices to our personal comfort and enjoyment to save the planet?<br /><br />Since finishing, climate change is all I can think about. Other things seem petty by comparison. Yes, this book is a downer, but we need smart people to be aware of the seriousness of climate change and to lead action if we're to have any hope of avoiding its worst consequences.<br /><br />PS I've only recently found out about carbon offsets--CO2 reducing projects, like forestation, that you can purchase to reduce your footprint--so at the very least, if I do fly, I'll purchase these.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3559886179007402359" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


