        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer58850483" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18284184011458257070">I read Six Degrees won the Royal Society popular science book of the year thingy in 2008 -- you know, solid science, but actually readable! Let me tell you, I&apos;m only up to four degrees, and I&apos;m *freaked*. I was having a conversation the other day about how global warming isn&apos;t about long hot summers, but a couple of degeres increase on average, across a whole year. Which is true, as it turns out but didn&apos;t go Nearly Far Enough. This guy is going through what happens at each of one through six de</span>
  <span id="freeText18284184011458257070" style="display:none">I read Six Degrees won the Royal Society popular science book of the year thingy in 2008 -- you know, solid science, but actually readable! Let me tell you, I'm only up to four degrees, and I'm *freaked*. I was having a conversation the other day about how global warming isn't about long hot summers, but a couple of degeres increase on average, across a whole year. Which is true, as it turns out but didn't go Nearly Far Enough. This guy is going through what happens at each of one through six degrees, on average, per year, hotter. Not a *lot* warmer, right? Ho. And also, ha. It sort of makes me want to yell and scream at people to turn all the fucking carbon burning stuff right the fuck off, *now*, so I don't die of heat stroke when I'm seventy, as looks really quite likely.<br /><br />I may need to go read some climate change denial fiction just to deal with the fact that honestly, in the absolute worst case scenario there's not much I can do by myself. Except move to a house with solar panels and a decent sized garden set at least 75 metres above sea level O.O. And maybe buy a desalination kit and a small boat. Irony: I have my driving licence until I'm seventy, in 2040, okay? At the current rates of change, the Arctic circle will be ice free in the summer of 2040. Never mind no fuel for cars, I'm starting to think there may not be roads.</span>
  <a data-text-id="18284184011458257070" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


