<div id="review_133043387" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/133043387" />
    <a title="Steve" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/334225-steve"><img alt="Steve" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/133043387?book_show_action=true">Nov 30, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Steve" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Steve" href="/user/show/334225-steve">Steve</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780007209040" href="/book/show/227477.Six_Degrees">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/334225-steve?shelf=fun-nonfiction">fun-nonfiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/334225-steve?shelf=the-natural-world">the-natural-world</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer133043387" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8623444737352041197">This is the scariest book I&apos;ve read in a long, long time.<br/><br/>It lays out in detail what each degree of global warming will entail (the current expected range of warming is somewhere between 1.5 and now possibly up to 8 degrees Celsius), and how that will affect life on Earth. We are already locked into experiencing the first chapter, which is the likely return of the American Great Plains to desert. Each successive chapter just gets worse, and describes positive feedback systems which will make thin</span>
  <span id="freeText8623444737352041197" style="display:none">This is the scariest book I've read in a long, long time.<br /><br />It lays out in detail what each degree of global warming will entail (the current expected range of warming is somewhere between 1.5 and now possibly up to 8 degrees Celsius), and how that will affect life on Earth. We are already locked into experiencing the first chapter, which is the likely return of the American Great Plains to desert. Each successive chapter just gets worse, and describes positive feedback systems which will make things warmer and warmer, the warmer it gets -- by the end of the book, Lynas has gone from talking about adaptations to 'zones of uninhabitability' to 'zones of inhabitability' -- where much of the Earth's surface will simply no longer be suitable for humans to live on.<br /><br />The book itself is very well-written and easy to follow, and is taken from climate science papers.<br /><br />The scariest part is that the one bit of hope Lynas offers, that we have some time to avert a more than 2C rise in temperatures, was just this week (November, 2010) declared to be almost impossible to achieve given the current political situation.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8623444737352041197" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


